##This "kidney team" specializes in dealing with an "inflammatory storm. "

Wechat, bingdianweekly

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Nurses at a blood purification center wait for aid to arrive at Guanggu Hospital district of Tongji Hospital in Wuhan, Hubei Province on Feb. 26. The "kidney care team" , made up of more than 20 specialized nursing staff, is responsible for blood purification and cytokine storm clearing for patients with severe and critically ill new coronary pneumonia. China Youth Daily Reporter, Li Junhui

This is a photo report by Li Junhui, a reporter of the CYB

From the evening of the New Year's Eve, Wuhan Tongji Hospital Blood Purification Center nurse Yan Jianjun and his team has not had a rest, has been more than a month.

February 9, Wuhan Tongji Hospital Guanggu Hospital area was requisitioned for the new severe pneumonia treatment hospital. More than two days, here quickly filled with more than 800 seriously ill and critically ill patients. On the day of the raid, Yan and the nurses completed dialysis for more than 100 patients and transferred them back to their home district. It was midnight.

Two days later, more than 40 nurses at the blood purification center split in two. Half of the "youngest and most capable" nurses returned to Guanggu Hospital district to form a "kidney team" to start dialysis for patients with new coronary pneumonia. These patients are two weeks ago, "inventory" , then "should be collected" policy has not been issued, many patients because of false negative nucleic acid testing delay treatment, only to be sent to the hospital after the deterioration.

The work of the "kidney team" is first to screen patients with kidney damage, early intervention to avoid kidney damage, and second to screen for inflammatory cytokines. They found that many patients were at risk for "cytokine storms" . In patients with underlying diseases, a "cytokine storm" can cause multiple organ dysfunction syndrome that can lead to death. Blood purification technology can protect organs and save lives by removing inflammatory factors. "blood purification therapy" will be added if there is a cytokine storm in severe or critically ill patients, according to the seventh edition of the diagnosis and treatment plan for COVID-19 pneumonia, which was released by the National Health Commission on March 3.

February 26, Wuhan Tongji Hospital Guanggu Hospital district, Blood Purification Center nurses Feng Baiqian, Wanniu, Li Jiming (left to right) in the morning shift meeting. All the Nurses Punch in at 8:00 every morning and report their condition. China Youth Daily reporter Li Junhui / photo

With the current team's staffing, dialysis for 10 patients a day is the norm and a full-time job. Once in the ICU, the nurses adjust the blood purifier, and the doctors begin to intubate the patient, which can be difficult in two or three layers of protective clothing, what could have been done in half an hour takes an hour. A patient uses the blood purifier for 8-10 hours, while a health care worker uses the protective clothing for 6 hours, so it takes two sets of nurses to complete a patient's blood purification, some nurses are even in the ICU three times a day.

ICU is the red zone in the red zone, the concentration of virus aerosol in the room is very high, close to the operation needs two or even three-level protection (three is the highest protection) , protective clothing if there is a little leak, the virus may be inhaled. It's also a high level of Hypoxia, and every time they come out of the ICU, they're drenched in sweat.

At the beginning of the epidemic, patients who needed regular dialysis still had to go to the hospital two or three times a week, and the dialysis room was a place where people gathered and there was a high risk of infection. Dialysis patients are often associated with underlying diseases, and once infected, the mortality rate is extremely high. The medical staff who operate dialysis are also at great risk.

Constant infection of medical staff, the news of diagnosis, will have an impact on the psychological first-line nurses. "To be honest, we are all scared. But hemodialysis is the last way to save a patient's life. If you do it, the patient may live, but if you don't do it, you will die, " Yan said.

"closed city" early, a lot of materials did not have time to bring in, isolation clothes used up, doctors and nurses can only wear overalls or even patients' hospital gowns to work, until the 15th day of the first month after the situation slowly improved. In the meantime, hospitals were being requisitioned in Wuhan, and patients on regular dialysis had no place to go. Once they have a fever, could have gone to dialysis hospital does not allow reception, can only be transferred to designated hospitals screening. "because there was no dialysis during the screening, many patients didn't make it, " Yan said. Later, dialysis patients have a designated hospital, plus the entry of provincial medical teams, the situation has improved.

He Fan, associate professor of nephrology at Tongji Hospital, said that at the beginning, the aid medical teams in Guanggu district held a conservative attitude towards the application of blood purification technology in the treatment of patients with new coronary pneumonia. Once, "kidney squad" for a 74-year-old man after three times of blood purification, initially respiratory failure, has entered the coma state of the elderly gradually began to improve, more than 30 times normal levels of inflammatory factors returned to normal. A week later, the old man was transferred to a hospital after his severe illness became less severe. From then on, this kind of treatment began to be accepted by the medical teams. Over the next two weeks, 34 patients underwent nearly 100 blood purification procedures, and 10 of them were discharged or transferred to a mild-illness hospital.

Figures from the joint prevention and Control Mechanism of the State Council at a press conference on February 29 showed that the state has sent more than 5,500 nurses in the medical teams in Hubei and Wuhan, accounting for about 21 percent of the total number of stationed nurses, nurses in the critical care field account for three quarters of the total number of critical care medical personnel. The medical team mainly consisted of doctors in the departments of aspiration, infection and critical care, and few doctors and nurses in the departments of Kidney.

Patients who require blood purification are critically ill, have a high risk of cytokine storms, and require intensive care. The consumption of human resources is very high, which leads to the shortage of professional nurses for hemodialysis in Wuhan.

"It's not that I don't want to change, it's that no one will, " Yan said. In his view, now is the most difficult period, if the stock of cases can be digested, there are no confirmed patients outside, no one is getting worse, then it can be a relief. "It's like a sniper battle right now, everyone is tired, there's even the problem of losing people because of the infection, but you have to hold the position, you can't lose it, " he said. He Fan also called, hoping to have blood purification department nurses to Wuhan to support them, "after all, has been overloaded for a long time. ".
